**Additional Context**
This model was converted from a tflite model using [this notebook](https://colab.research.google.com/gist/josephrocca/401efe82bf18ffe93d5f3deca7ed7515/notebook.ipynb) - there were no errors or warnings. issue.title: [Web] ONNX Runtime throws undescriptive exception

labels.name: platform:web
labels.description: issues related to ONNX Runtime web; typically submitted using template

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
### Describe the issue

In the default configuration published to NPM, ONNX Runtime is compiled without exception support in emscripten, but it still makes heavy of use of C++ exceptions. As a result, it still calls into emscripten C++ exception code, which is stubbed out, and throws the C++ exception pointer as a JS exception (without even wrapping it into a WebAssembly.Exception or JS Error).
The C++ exception pointer appears a bare number, and it lacks context (stack) or even an error message, so it is essentially useless to debug what is going wrong.

I think ONNX Runtime should either compile with emscripten exceptions enabled (given it makes use of C++ exceptions), or it should disable C++ exceptions completely, and report errors in a different way that preserves error message.
Compiling with native WASM exceptions would be best, as it gives best performance and best observability. It is supported by all recent browsers: https://webassembly.org/roadmap/

### To reproduce

There are different ways to trigger C++ exceptions, and I don't know all of them (if I did, I could guard against all of them, and avoid this issue entirely). One way I know of is to pass an input that is too large for the model, which triggers a C++ exception in BroadcastIterator. Another way is to run out of WASM memory, which causes std::bad_alloc.

### Urgency

This issue makes it very hard to deploy ONNX Runtime in production, because without observability if errors occur one is stuck with no debugging options, but the alternative is to deploy a custom debug build, which does not seem appropriate for production.

### ONNX Runtime Installation

Released Package

### ONNX Runtime Version or Commit ID

onnxruntime-web@npm:1.12.1

### Execution Provider

WASM

Sorry for the delay in response. We have some progress on the issue - I was able to find that the model might has issues to run with ORT. here is the error -

The input tensor cannot be reshaped to the requested shape. Input shape:{1,320,1}, requested shape:{1,1,1,368}

There might be an issue with the conversion - @josephrocca, where you able to run the model on ORT without ORT Web?
I am continuing to debug the issue but if you have a working set up it will help to isolate the problem.

In regards of the broader issue of exception handling, we are aware of the limited debugging capabilities with the current build, and we are examining different ways to address the problem. Right now, we know how to retrieve the debug messages, but it requires a re-build. Our team is looking at a few option that might resolve the problem and how enable exception throwing will impact ORT Web. I will update soon with the decision - and I will also update (https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/13408).

Thanks

Hi @shalvamist, I've just tested it and am seeing the same error in ORT Python. Here's a minimal reproduction:

https://colab.research.google.com/gist/josephrocca/91e876fd90e6b7c88429258ba2384a36/onnx-runtime-python-inference.ipynb

But I think the particular problem in my case may be due to a tf2onnx conversion issue. Please see [this comment](https://github.com/onnx/tensorflow-onnx/issues/2059#issuecomment-1296301499) and the ones above it for more context.

Hi @josephrocca,

Thanks for sharing the colab, this aligns with my findings. (The errors match)
Since you already have an ongoing discussion on the conversion it seems like the right place to resolve the issue.
I will update this thread with the upcoming PR regarding exception handling. Please let me know if you need anything else related to the issue or ORT Web.
Thanks @shalvamist - the other commenters likely having different issues so I'm reluctant to close, but I think this is best tracked at #13408? I'll close it and let you re-open if needed.

issue.title: for wasm catch exceptions at top level api

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
fix for https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/13383, https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/13408

Currently ort-web doesn't catch exceptions because turning on exception catching increases the binary size by 3MB (~30%).
But ort can throw (ie onnx errors or ORT_ENFORCE) and there is no useable error message.

Turning on exception catching just for top level api released file will fix the error messages at minimal increase of binary size.
